QC

QC is very important because you need to filter out low-quality cells, such as:

  • dead cells
  • empty cells
  • doublets/multiplets

Remember we all ready did some filtering when creating objects for each sample. This is with min.cells and min.features.

CreateSeuratObject(counts, project = 'pasca', min.cells = 3, min.features = 100)

For this main QC part, we will be filtering cells based on these 4 variables:

  • nCount (nCount_RNA) = # of transcripts per cell
  • nFeature (nFeature_RNA) = # of genes detected per cell
  • percent.mt = % mitochondrial genes detected per cell
  • percent.rb = % ribosomal genes detected per cell

Calculate mitocondrial and ribosomal reads

Before we filter, we need to calculate percent.mt and percent.rb variables. We can either find these genes with a regex pattern or put in a gene list.

Gene names between human and mouse are different.

For human:

  • mitochondrial genes = ^MT-
  • ribosomal genes = ^RP[SL]

For mouse:

  • mitochondrial genes = ^mt-
  • ribosomal genes = ^Rp[sl]
# calculate percentage of a gene set
# ?PercentageFeatureSet

# with regex pattern
head(PercentageFeatureSet(object = obs[[1]], pattern = '^MT-'))

# with gene list
gene_list <- rownames(obs[[1]])[grep('^MT-',rownames(obs[[1]]))]

Lets now calculate percent.mt and percent.rb for every sample object. These variables will then be stored in the metadata slot in each object.

# calculate mitochondria and ribosomal reads for each cell in each object
for (i in 1:length(obs)) {
  obs[[i]]$percent.mt <- PercentageFeatureSet(obs[[i]], pattern = "^MT-")
  obs[[i]]$percent.rb <- PercentageFeatureSet(obs[[i]], pattern = '^RP[SL]')
}

# percentages for mt and rb are stored in metadata slot for each object

One Sample QC

Now we can do QC and filtering. To make it simple at first, lets do it on one sample. We will be using the AdjNorm_TISSUE_1 sample for this example. This is obs[[1]] in our list of objects.

Before Filtering

The first step is to look at violin and scatter plots of the 4 QC variables.

  • violin plot = looking at variables individually
# ?VlnPlot
  • scatter plot = looking at combination of 2 variables
# ?FeaturePlot


Remember, we want to get the cells that represent the majority of the distribution.

# plot violin plot of QC variables AdjNorm_TISSUE_1 sample QC

Picking Thresholds

The second step is to pick the thresholds for all 4 QC variables. There will be a low threshold and high threshold. The cells in the range of these thresholds will be kept, and cells outside will be filtered out. For the high threshold, overestimating it is fine. You dont want to filter out too many cells.

# get range of QC variables AdjNorm_TISSUE_1 sample QC
## this will give you the min and max of the current variables
nCount_RNA_range <- range(obs[[1]]$nCount_RNA)
nFeature_RNA_range <- range(obs[[1]]$nFeature_RNA)
percent.mt_range <- range(obs[[1]]$percent.mt)
percent.rb_range <- range(obs[[1]]$percent.rb)

nCount_RNA_range
## [1]    500 733526
# fill in list of filtering thresholds for each QC variable
## each vector in list should contain 2 values (low threshold, high threshold)
vln_y_line <- list(
  nCount_RNA = c(nCount_RNA_range[1],3e5), 
  nFeature_RNA = c(nFeature_RNA_range[1], 8000), 
  percent.mt = c(percent.mt_range[1],20), 
  percent.rb = c(percent.rb_range[1],percent.rb_range[2])
)

vln_y_line

The third step is to check that the thresholds look good with plots. We will add threshold lines to show where we am filtering. I do this step to make sure I didnt mistype any values or if I want to change the threshold before actually filtering.

# violin plots with threshold lines
plot1 <- VlnPlot(obs[[1]], features = c("nCount_RNA"), pt.size = 0) & geom_hline(yintercept = c(vln_y_line[[1]][1], vln_y_line[[1]][2])) & theme(legend.position = 'none')
plot2 <- VlnPlot(obs[[1]], features = c("nFeature_RNA"), pt.size = 0) & geom_hline(yintercept = c(vln_y_line[[2]][1], vln_y_line[[2]][2])) & theme(legend.position = 'none')
plot3 <- VlnPlot(obs[[1]], features = c("percent.mt"), pt.size = 0) & geom_hline(yintercept = c(vln_y_line[[3]][1], vln_y_line[[3]][2])) & theme(legend.position = 'none')
plot4 <- VlnPlot(obs[[1]], features = c("percent.rb"), pt.size = 0) & geom_hline(yintercept = c(vln_y_line[[4]][1], vln_y_line[[4]][2])) & theme(legend.position = 'none')

wrap_plots(plot1, plot2, plot3, plot4, ncol = 2, nrow = 2)

plot2 <- FeatureScatter(object = obs[[1]], feature1 = "nCount_RNA", feature2 = "percent.rb") & geom_hline(yintercept = c(vln_y_line[[4]][1], vln_y_line[[4]][2])) & geom_vline(xintercept = c(vln_y_line[[1]][1], vln_y_line[[1]][2])) & theme(legend.position = 'none')

plot1 + plot2 + plot3 + plot4

Filtering

The fourth step is to actually filter with the thresholds we have chosen. We will be using this function:

# ?subset

obs[[1]] <- subset(obs[[1]], subset = 
                     (nCount_RNA >= vln_y_line[[1]][1] & 
                        nCount_RNA <= vln_y_line[[1]][2]) & 
                     (nFeature_RNA >= vln_y_line[[2]][1] & 
                        nFeature_RNA <= vln_y_line[[2]][2]) & 
                     (percent.mt >= vln_y_line[[3]][1] & 
                        percent.mt <= vln_y_line[[3]][2]) & 
                     (percent.rb >= vln_y_line[[4]][1] & 
                        percent.rb <= vln_y_line[[4]][2])
              )


You dont actually have to specify all the thresholds when filtering/subsetting. In this sample, we only filtered on nCount, nFeature, and percent.mt, so we dont have to include percent.rb in the function. Also, we didnt set any new low thresholds, so we dont have to specify those thresholds either.

The code will look like this:

## DO NOT RUN
# obs[[1]] <- subset(obs[[1]], subset = nCount_RNA <= 3e5 & nFeature_RNA <= 8000 & percent.mt <= 20)

I have only included all the thresholds (low and high) for automated processing reasons. You will see this later on in the script when we filter all sample objects at once.

After Filtering

The fifth step is to check that filtering worked and it looks good with plots. If you did mess up, you can go back to the raw objects by reloading the pasca_raw_objects.rds file.

VlnPlot(obs[[1]], features = c("nCount_RNA", "nFeature_RNA", "percent.mt", "percent.rb"), ncol = 4, pt.size = .5)

All Samples QC

We will now filter all the samples at once. This code is specialized to filter on each sample object to make it automated. This helps with making the code clean by reducing duplicated code. The difference for this specialized code for all samples is that the main functions are wrapped around in loops. Also, it automatically saves plots as png files outside of R.

We will reload the raw objects, but we will keep the thresholds we found above for the first sample.

Exercise: Picking Thresholds

Choose the thresholds for the other 5 samples:

  • AdjNorm_TISSUE_2
  • AdjNorm_TISSUE_3
  • PDAC_TISSUE_1
  • PDAC_TISSUE_2
  • PDAC_TISSUE_3

We already did AdjNorm_TISSUE_1 together, so dont change those values!

Make sure you include a low and high threshold in every vector for each variable for each sample (otherwise youll get an error). Since we arent setting a low threshold, please dont change the first element of each vector. Also, dont worry about filtering on percent.rb. Please dont change those values in any sample.

ex: nCount_RNA = c(nCount_RNA_range[[1]][1],{high threshold})

The elements/values you can change will have {val} as a placeholder.

You can check your thresholds with the plots. You will have to run the whole for loop to save and see the plots outside of R.

Unbatched Analysis

Before considering integration, I like to analyze my dataset ignoring batch effect first even if I know that it has a batch effect. I mainly do this so I can for sure check to make sure what my batch variable(s) is. It also allows for transparency that serves as proof that you have a batch effect and that it was corrected for in the main figures in your articles.

Merge objects

Since our objects are separated by sample, we will have to merge the objects together before we can do the rest of the standard pipeline. We will go over the integration pipeline later on.

# long format
## DO NOT RUN
# merged_ob <- merge(x = obs[[1]], y = c(obs[[2]], obs[[3]], obs[[4]], obs[[5]], obs[[6]]), add.cell.ids = metadata$sample_id)

# short, cleaner format
## need to include add.cell.ids (adds sample name to barcode name)
more_obs <- paste0("c(",paste(sapply(2:length(obs),function(i) paste0("obs[[",i,"]]")),collapse=",",sep=""),")")
merged_ob <- merge(obs[[1]], eval(parse(text=more_obs)), add.cell.ids = metadata$sample_id)

# cell names before merge
head(colnames(obs[[1]]))
## [1] "AAACCCAGTCCGACGT-1" "AAACCCAGTGTCGCTG-1" "AAACCCATCTGCACCT-1"
## [4] "AAACGAAAGCGACCCT-1" "AAACGAAAGCGGACAT-1" "AAACGAAAGTCACACT-1"

Normalization

Normalization transforms the distribution of the data, which, in this scRNA-seq analysis, it transform the data into a more normal distribution. Normalization helps to reduce unwanted variation, compare among samples better, and make the values easier to see (can see differences better).

We will use this function:

# run normalization
# ?NormalizeData
merged_ob <- NormalizeData(merged_ob)

Find Variable Features

We have over 10,000 genes in this dataset. We want to find the genes that will give us the most information without using all of the genes. These genes will have the most variance (aka the most variable).

We will use this function to find the most variable genes:

# find most variable genes
# ?FindVariableFeatures
merged_ob <- FindVariableFeatures(merged_ob)

We will choose the top 2000 genes for this example. You can change the # of variable genes, and this will change the results. When choosing the # of variable genes, overestimating is usually better than underestimating.


We can look at our variable genes with this function:

# Scatter plot of average expression and standardized variance 
## each dot is a gene

top10_list <- head(VariableFeatures(merged_ob), 10)
p1 <- VariableFeaturePlot(merged_ob)
p2 <- LabelPoints(plot = p1, points = top10_list)

Check Cell Cycle Batch

Cell cycle can affect the results, so we need to do QC on it. We will be looking at the G1, S, and G2/M phases.

For human, you can find a curated list of cell cycle genes in Seurat with the code below. For mouse, you will have to find or make a cell cycle gene list.

# human cc genes found in Seurat
## might not find all of these genes in dataset (might give warning about that)
cc_genes <- cc.genes.updated.2019


To check cell cycle QC, we can run the code below:

# calculate scores
# ?CellCycleScoring
merged_ob <- CellCycleScoring(merged_ob, s.features = cc_genes$s.genes, g2m.features = cc_genes$g2m.genes, set.ident = TRUE)

# scale data on cc genes

If you decide to correct for cell cycle, we can check how its corrected with the codes below:

  • Method 1: Regress out all cell cycle effects
# scale on cc genes and regress on the S and G2/M scores
merged_ob <- ScaleData(merged_ob, features = c(cc_genes$s.genes, cc_genes$g2m.genes),
                   vars.to.regress = c('S.Score', 'G2M.Score'), verbose = F) 

# run PCA on fully regressed cc genes
merged_ob <- RunPCA(object = merged_ob, features = c(cc_genes$s.genes, cc_genes$g2m.genes), 
                    nfeatures.print = 5, reduction.name = 'cc_pca', verbose = F)
## Warning in irlba(A = t(x = object), nv = npcs, ...): You're computing too large
## a percentage of total singular values, use a standard svd instead.
# plot PCA of cc phases
DimPlot(merged_ob, reduction = 'cc_pca', group.by = 'Phase')

  • Method 2: Regress out some cell cycle effects
# will only see differences between non-cycling (G1) and cycling cells (S and G2/M)

# subtract S and G2/M scores
merged_ob$CC.Difference <- merged_ob$S.Score - merged_ob$G2M.Score

# scale on cc genes regressing out difference between S and G2/M phases
merged_ob <- ScaleData(merged_ob, features = c(cc_genes$s.genes, cc_genes$g2m.genes),
                   vars.to.regress = c("CC.Difference"), verbose = F) 

# run PCA on regressed cc genes
merged_ob <- RunPCA(object = merged_ob, features = c(cc_genes$s.genes, cc_genes$g2m.genes), 
                    nfeatures.print = 5, reduction.name = 'cc_pca', verbose = F)

Scaling

Scaling changes the range of values (not the distribution like normalization does). The values are centered around a mean with a unit standard deviation. Scaling helps to reduce unwanted variation and is required to run PCA in Seurat (otherwise you will get an error).

We will use this function:

# scale data
# ?ScaleData
merged_ob <- ScaleData(merged_ob, vars.to.regress = 'nCount_RNA') 
## Regressing out nCount_RNA
## Centering and scaling data matrix

We will regress on nCount to reduce variation from library preparation among cells. You can add more variables like percent.mt if you decide to. You dont even have to regress on any variable if you dont need it.


We will only scale on the top 2000 variable genes because it will make the processing go a lot faster, and we will not be using the Seurat plot functions that require scaled data. Remember that we wont be able to find genes outside of the top 2000 variable genes list. Ultimately, we will only be using the variable genes to get good clustering and UMAPs.

# genes x cells of scaled data

PCA helps to reduce the dimension of the dataset or # of variables used for downstream analyses. In scRNA-seq, dimensions are genes.

# run PCA
# ?RunPCA
merged_ob <- RunPCA(merged_ob, features = VariableFeatures(merged_ob),  nfeatures.print = 5)

We will run on the top 2000 variable genes, which is the default in Seurat.


To choose how many PCs to use in downstream analyses, we will look at the PCA in two ways:

  • Qualitative method
# scree/elbow plot
# ?ElbowPlot
ElbowPlot(merged_ob, ndims = 50)


We will not do a JackStraw plot because it takes a long time to run (and I dont normally use it). However, here is the code for it:

# JackStraw plot
## DO NOT RUN
# merged_ob <- JackStraw(merged_ob)
# merged_ob <- ScoreJackStraw(merged_ob, dims = 1:20)
# JackStrawPlot(merged_ob, dims = 1:20)
  • Quantitative method
# complex method - make range of PCs for high threshold 
## will choose minimum value of this range
pct <- merged_ob@reductions$pca@stdev / sum(merged_ob@reductions$pca@stdev) * 100 
cum <- cumsum(pct) 
co1 <- which(cum > 90 & pct < 5)[1] 
co2 <- sort(which((pct[1:length(pct)-1] - pct[2:length(pct)]) > .1), decreasing = T)[1] + 1
pcs <- min(co1, co2) 

# will use 1-18 PCs for downstream analyses


This is also a good place to check for potential batch effects.

# PCA plot (with sample_id)
DimPlot(merged_ob, reduction = 'pca', group.by = 'sample_id')

Clustering

Clustering is an unsupervised technique. It divides data points into groups with similar traits and assigns them as clusters. In scRNA-seq, data points are cells. Seurat uses a graph-based method, and it does it in two steps:

  1. Find neighbors using KNN graph
  2. Find clusters using Louvain algorithm

We will use the code below:

# find neighbors
# ?FindNeighbors
## pcs = 18
merged_ob <- FindNeighbors(merged_ob, dims = 1:pcs, k.param = 20)
## Computing nearest neighbor graph
## Computing SNN
# find clusters
# ?FindClusters
merged_ob <- FindClusters(merged_ob)
## Modularity Optimizer version 1.3.0 by Ludo Waltman and Nees Jan van Eck
## 
## Number of nodes: 13082
## Number of edges: 457331
## 
## Running Louvain algorithm...
## Maximum modularity in 10 random starts: 0.9423
## Number of communities: 30
## Elapsed time: 2 seconds


We will use the PCA results from above when clustering, which is the default in Seurat. We will also use a resolution 0.8, which is the default in Seurat. To increase the # of clusters, you can increase the resolution.

Non-Linear Dimension Reduction - UMAP

Non-linear dimension reduction methods learn the underlying manifold of the data to place similar cells together in a low-dimensional space. The main methods used in scRNA-seq are tSNE and UMAP. We will be using UMAP for this example. For both methods, we will use the PCs to speed up processing.

If you want to run tSNE, the code is below:

## DO NOT RUN
# ?RunTSNE
# merged_ob <- RunTSNE(merged_ob, dims = 1:pcs)


Code to run UMAP is below:

# run UMAP
# ?RunUMAP
merged_ob <- RunUMAP(merged_ob, dims = 1:pcs)

From these UMAPs plotted by clusters, sample_id, and condition, we can see that there are potential batch effect variables. We will choose sample_id as the main batch effect variable. We could have chosen condition, but sample_id also takes into account condition. We will use this batch variable in the integration pipeline.

DE

DE is where you can run comparison tests. The examples shown below do not account for batch effect.

Finding DE genes for clusters

By doing DE on clusters, we can see what genes makes each cluster different from each other. When we are testing, we are comparing one cluster to the rest of the cells (ignoring cluster).

We can use the function below to do this:

# ?FindMarkers
de_unbatch_0 <- FindMarkers(merged_ob, ident.1 = 0)

head(de_unbatch_0)

## CD52      0   1.298735 0.873 0.309         0
## LCK       0   1.290523 0.618 0.132         0
## CD2       0   2.191710 0.880 0.150         0
## RPS27     0   1.354173 0.999 0.897         0
## CD247     0   1.075670 0.617 0.122         0

Instead of running all the clusters right now, I have run it for you because it can take a long time. You can load in the full DE table with the code below:

de <- read_csv('D:/scRNA-seq pipeline/pasca_dataset/tables/cds_pasca_example_cluster0_de_032222.csv')
## Rows: 2273 Columns: 6
## -- Column specification --------------------------------------------------------
## Delimiter: ","
## chr (1): gene
## dbl (5): p_val, avg_log2FC, pct.1, pct.2, p_val_adj
## 
## i Use `spec()` to retrieve the full column specification for this data.
## i Specify the column types or set `show_col_types = FALSE` to quiet this message.

Here are descriptions of the columns in the DE table:

  • p_val = p-value (not adjusted)
  • avg_log2FC = log2 fold-change (FC) of average expression between 2 groups
    • log2(FC1) - log2(FC2)
    • Positive (+) value = higher in group 1
    • Negative (-) value = lower in group 1
  • pct.1/pct.2 = % of cells where gene is expressed in group (1 or 2)
    • expressed = normalized expression > 0
  • p_val_adj = adjusted p-value
    • by Bonferroni
  • cluster = name of group compared
    • this is group 1
  • gene = name of gene

To find the most important DE genes, we can do the code below:

# filter by adjusted p-value < .05
## make sure you are looking at significant genes
de_filt <- de %>% dplyr::filter(p_val_adj < .05)

# sort by average log2FC (most positive to most negative)
de_filt <- de_filt %>% arrange(-avg_log2FC)

# can condense code and write as:
## DO NOT RUN
# de_filt <- de %>% dplyr::filter(p_val_adj < .05) %>% arrange(cluster, -avg_log2FC)

Finding DE genes between groups

To find DE genes between groups, its very similar to finding for clusters.

# run DE for N vs. P condition
de_condition <- FindMarkers(merged_ob, ident.1 = 'N', ident.2 = 'P', group.by = 'condition')
de_condition_filt <- de_condition %>% rownames_to_column('gene') %>% dplyr::filter(p_val_adj < .05) %>% arrange(-avg_log2FC)
